<TITLE> 27th BCS protestors get bail </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 3 (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court on Wednesday granted bail to 17 of the 27th BCS first-round finalists who were detained on charges of laying siege to the Public Service Commission office the previous day. Chief metropolitan magistrate Saifur Rahman Siddiqui awarded the bail after the detained demonstrators moved the court for a second time. The 17 arrestees had moved for bail on Tuesday, but the court rejected the prayer and ordered them into custody. Defence counsel Abdullah Al Mansur told the court on Wednesday that the his 17 arrested clients were "attacked by the police" while protesting "peacefully" around the PSC office. Some 60 ex-candidatesfirst-round qualifiers of the 27th BCS qualifiers who failed to pass in the second-round retakeslocked the main gate of the PSC building and smashed windowpanes of the building at around 9am Tuesday, leaving the staffers stranded inside the building. In a related incident, a group of 27th BCS protestors went on a hunger-to-death demonstration at the Central Shaheed Minar from Nov 1 demanding that authorities upheld the first-round results. Education adviser Hossain Zillur Rahman broke their hunger strike on Nov. 20, assuring them of a "logical solution". bdnews24
